Duffy, Timothy    | Department of Comparative Literature | NYU       NYU > Comparative Literature > Timothy Duffy                        New York University       Arts and Science       College of Arts and Science       Graduate School of Arts and Science           Comparative Literature     &nbsp;                          Back to  previous page              &nbsp;       &nbsp;                   Duffy, Timothy   Assistant Professor/Faculty Fellow of Comparative Literature Ph.D., Virginia, 2013   Office Address: 19 University Place, rm 311, New York, NY 10003 Email:                 Curriculum Vitae                  Areas of Research/Interest   Renaissance lyric poetry, spatial science, mapmaking, geometry, the spatial turn              Before coming to NYU, Timothy Duffy taught  at the University of New Hampshire and the College of the Holy Cross. His  research centers on Renaissance lyric expression and spatial science and  philosophy, focusing especially on mapmaking, geometry, and the Renaissance  roots of the postmodern spatial turn.    His book project, "Lyric Projections: The Spatial Reformation of  the Renaissance Imagination" explores, in a comparative and multi-lingual  context, the spatial imagination of Renaissance poetry, epic, and drama as a  common engine for irenic devotional, scientific, and philosophical inquiry as  seen in the works of Petrarch, Joachim du Bellay, Edmund Spenser, William  Shakespeare, John Donne, and Richard Crashaw. His additional research interests  include epistolary discourse, theory of the lyric, cartographic theory,  psychoanalysis, and Renaissance influences on twentieth-century anthropological  writing.
